Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is GPT?
AI Response

GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) is an autoregressive language model trained to predict the next
token. GPT-3 and GPT-4 are large-scale versions capable of diverse language tasks.

Example 1.2

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.3

User

What is tokenization in NLP?
AI Response

Tokenization splits text into smaller units (tokens) such as words, subwords, or characters. Subword
tokenization (BPE, WordPiece) balances vocabulary size with handling of rare words.

Example 1.4

User

What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response

A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.

Example 1.5

User

What is a transformer model?
AI Response

A transformer is a deep learning architecture using self-attention mechanisms that process all tokens in
parallel, enabling efficient NLP. GPT and BERT are transformer-based models.

Example 1.6

User

What is zero-shot learning?
AI Response

Zero-shot learning predicts unseen classes by leveraging semantic relationships or natural language task
descriptions, allowing LLMs to generalize without task-specific training.

Example 1.7

User

What is an autoencoder?
AI Response



An autoencoder learns a compressed (latent) representation of input data through an encoder, then
reconstructs it with a decoder. Used for dimensionality reduction, denoising, and anomaly detection.

Example 1.8

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.9

User

What is dropout?
AI Response

Dropout randomly sets a fraction of neuron activations to zero during training, preventing co-adaptation of
neurons and reducing overfitting.

Example 1.10

User

What is RLHF?
AI Response

Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback trains a reward model on human preference data, then uses
RL (PPO) to fine-tune an LLM to produce outputs humans prefer.



